,"1364–1454":"1364–1454","1402–1462":"1402–1462","1415–1474":"1415–1474","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1335–Female":"1335–Deceased","after 1401":"after 1401","1415":"1415","1402":"1402","1335":"1335","1401":"1401","1454":"1454","1364":"1364","1474":"1474","1330":"1330","1462":"1462","circa 1454":"about 1454","Merchiston, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Merchiston, Midlothian, Scotland","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Napier","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name from Old French <i>napier</i>, <i>nappier</i>, <i>nap(p)er(er)</i> ‘one who looks after the napery or table-linen’, a derivative of Old French <i>nappe</i> ‘table-cloth, napkin’. In Middle English, <i>Napier</i> and <i>Nap(p)er</i> might also have denoted a maker of table cloths, though this sense has not been recorded.","English: alternatively an occupational name from <i>Nap(p)er</i> from an unrecorded Middle English word for one who makes <i>naps</i>, i.e. drinking cups or chalices (Middle English <i>nap</i>, Old English <i>hnæp</i>). <i>Napper</i> could also be a nickname from Middle English <i>nappere</i> ‘one who sleeps or naps’, though this is the least likely of the alternatives.","American shortened form of Polish   Napierala   or a similar name."],"variants":[{"name":"Napper","meanings":["English: variant of   Napier  .","Altered form of English or German   Knapper   or of German   Nepper  ."]},{"name":"Nappier","meanings":["English: variant of   Napier  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Napierala","meanings":["Polish (<b>Napierała</b>): nickname for an insistent person,from a derivative of <i>napierać</i> ‘advance, press, urge’."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Napier of Merchiston was born in 1364, in Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, William Napier, was 35 and his mother, Mrs William Napier, was 30. He had at least 2 sons. He died about 1454, in Merchiston, Midlothian, Scotland, at the age of 91."},"et":{"1364–circa 1454":"1364–umbes 1454","1364–1454":"1364–1454","1402–1462":"1402–1462","1415–1474":"1415–1474","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","after 1401":"pärast 1401","1415":"1415","1402":"1402","1335":"1335","1401":"1401","1454":"1454","1364":"1364","1474":"1474","1330":"1330","1462":"1462","circa 1454":"umbes 1454","Merchiston, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Merchiston, Midlothian, Scotland","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1364–circa 1454":"1364–noin 1454","1364–1454":"1364–1454","1402–1462":"1402–1462","1415–1474":"1415–1474","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","after 1401":"1401 jälkeen","1415":"1415","1402":"1402","1335":"1335","1401":"1401","1454":"1454","1364":"1364","1474":"1474","1330":"1330","1462":"1462","circa 1454":"noin 1454","Merchiston, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Merchiston, Midlothian, Scotland","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1364–circa 1454":"1364–environ 1454","1364–1454":"1364–1454","1402–1462":"1402–1462","1415–1474":"1415–1474","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1335–Female":"1335–Déc